Experimental Frequency Response (FRA)

After constructing the circuit on a breadboard, the filter response was measured using the Frequency Response Analysis (FRA) feature of the oscilloscope.The FRA measurement confirmed that the filter’s peak occurs near 17 kHz, closely matching the simulation results.This verifies that the physical circuit performs as expected and successfully isolates the target frequency.

 

Peak Detector Design

The output of the filter is still an AC waveform. To determine the presence of the signal, the waveform must be converted into a DC voltage proportional to the signal amplitude. This was accomplished using an op-amp peak detector circuit. The peak detector uses a diode and capacitor to store the peak voltage of the waveform. 
The design guideline from the lab states that the time constant should satisfy:
RC = 50T to 100T . where T is the period of the signal. For a 17 kHz signal ;
T = 1/17000 = 58.8 us
Using a 330 kΩ resistor, I used a capacitor value of 10nF which allows the detector to track peaks while maintaining a stable DC output. Below is the a picture of the peak detector graph.
 


Comparator Circuit

The DC voltage from the peak detector is compared to a reference voltage V {ref} using an LM339 comparator. The comparator determines whether the detected voltage corresponds to the presence of the desired frequency. The reference voltage is generated using a voltage divide.
Vpeak (17kHz) > Vref > Vpeak (10kHz, 25kHz)
This ensures that the LED activates only when the 17 kHz signal is present. Since the LM339 output is open collector, I used a  pull-up resistor 3 kΩ pull the output high when the comparator is off.

