Conclusion

A frequency detection circuit centered at 17 kHz was successfully designed, simulated, and implemented. The system consisted of a two-stage active band-pass filter, followed by a peak detector and an LM339 comparator used to drive an LED indicator. The band-pass filter was implemented using two cascaded second-order stages. Each stage contributes to the overall selectivity of the filter. The first stage was designed with a quality factor of approximately:
•	Q1 = 0.67
•	b1 = 1.49
The second stage was designed with a higher quality factor:
•	Q2 = 3
•	b2 = 0.33

This combination allowed me to make  the filter to achieve sufficient attenuation of unwanted frequencies while maintaining a strong response near the target frequency of 17 kHz. Simulation results obtained in LTspice showed a peak response around 17 kHz, with attenuation greater than 20 dB for undesired frequencies such as 10 kHz. These results were confirmed experimentally using the Frequency Response Analysis (FRA) feature of the oscilloscope. The filtered signal was then processed using a precision peak detector, which converted the AC signal into a DC voltage proportional to the signal amplitude. This voltage was compared to a reference voltage using an LM339 comparator. When the detected signal exceeded the reference threshold, the comparator output switched and activated an LED indicator.

